Here's an example C++ code that logs to a file using the Serilog framework:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <serilog/serilog.h>

int main() {
    // Create a Serilog logger that logs to a file
    std::string logPath = "log.txt";
    std::shared_ptr<spdlog::logger> logger   = spdlog::basic_logger_mt("basic_logger", logPath);

    // Log a message to the logger
    logger->info("Hello, Serilog!");

    return 0;
}
```
In this example, `log.txt` is the name and location of the log file. The logger is created using the `basic_logger_mt` function, and then a message is logged using the `info` method of the logger.

Note that in order to use this code, you must have the Serilog C++ package and its dependencies installed on your system. Also, you may need to adjust the include and linker paths in your project settings to properly link to these libraries.

Here's an updated C++ code that logs a message to a Kafka topic via the Serilog framework:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <serilog/serilog.h>
#include <librdkafka/rdkafka.h>

int main() {
    // Set up the Kafka producer
    std::string brokers = "localhost:9092";
    std::string topic = "my_topic";
    rd_kafka_t *rk;
    rd_kafka_conf_t *conf;
    char errstr[512];

    conf = rd_kafka_conf_new();
    if (rd_kafka_conf_set(conf, "bootstrap.servers", brokers.c_str(), errstr, sizeof(errstr)) != RD_KAFKA_CONF_OK) {
        std::cerr << "error configuring Kafka: " << errstr << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    rk = rd_kafka_new(RD_KAFKA_PRODUCER, conf, errstr, sizeof(errstr));
    if (!rk) {
        std::cerr << "error creating Kafka producer: " << errstr << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Create a Serilog logger that logs to Kafka
    std::shared_ptr<spdlog::logger> logger =
        spdlog::create<spdlog::sinks::kafka_sink_mt>("kafka_logger", rd_kafka_topic_partition_available, rd_kafka_topic_partition_produced, brokers, topic);

    // Log a message to the logger
    logger->info("Hello, Serilog with Kafka!");

    // Flush the logger and Kafka producer
    logger->flush();
    rd_kafka_flush(rk, 10000);

    // Destroy the Kafka producer and logger
    rd_kafka_destroy(rk);
    spdlog::drop("kafka_logger");

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, a Kafka producer is set up using the `librdkafka` library, and connected to the local Kafka cluster. Then, a `kafka_sink_mt` is created by the logger, and the logger is instructed to log using this sink with the specified Kafka brokers and topic. Finally, a log message with the `info` level is written to the logger, and both the logger and Kafka producer are flushed before being destroyed.

Note that you must have the `librdkafka` library and Serilog C++ package installed on your system. You may also need to adjust the include and linker paths in your project settings to properly link to these libraries.
